        <headline>Special Weather Statement issued June 19 at 4:27PM EDT by NWS Charleston WV</headline>
        <description>At 427 PM EDT, Doppler radar was tracking a cluster of strong
thunderstorms along a line extending from 8 miles southeast of
Buckhannon to 7 miles west of Holly River State Park. Movement was
east at 45 mph.

HAZARD...Wind gusts up to 40 mph and pea size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor hail damage to vegetation is
possible.

Locations impacted include...
Elkins, Mill Creek, Dailey, Holly River State Park, Beverly, Junior,
Durbin, Womelsdorf (Coalton), Huttonsville, Harman, Alexander, Cheat
Bridge, Dryfork, Eden, Glady, Helvetia, Pickens, Cleveland, Bowden,
and Hacker Valley.

This includes Route 33 between mile markers 31 and 35.
</description>
        <instruction>If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with these storms and may lead
to localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

To report severe weather, contact your nearest law enforcement
agency. They will relay your report to the National Weather Service
office in Charleston West Virginia.</instruction>
